ribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Oh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."]}]},{"name":"Leuchars","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from Leuchars (Fife)."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewars","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leuchars  ."]},{"name":"Lewers","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewer  .","Scottish: variant of <b>Leuchars</b>, a habitational name from Leuchars in Fife. The placename derives from Gaelic <i>luachar</i> ‘reed, rush’ + the English plural <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ness","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."],"variants":[{"name":"Neassa","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."]},{"name":"Neasa","meanings":["Traditional name of unknown origin; borne by a character in <i>Táin Bó Cuailgne</i> (the Cattle Raid of Cooley), the mother of Conchobhar."]},{"name":"Vanessa","meanings":["Name invented by  Jonathan Swift  (  1667–1745 ) for his friend  Esther Vanhomrigh . It seems to have been derived from the first syllable of her (Dutch) surname, with the addition of the suffix <i>-essa</i> (perhaps influenced by the first syllable of her given name). The name became fairly popular in the 20th century, being borne for example by the actress  Vanessa Redgrave  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord William of Ness o Leuchars was born in 1061, in Leuchars, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of M Leuchare and F Leuchars. He had at least 2 sons with Matilda de Senlis. He died in 1120, in Somme, Picardie, 